**PROGRAM 5 : Linear Search**

**AIM** 

To write a C program that performs linear search on an array to find a specific element entered by the user.

**ALGORITHM**

Start the program.

Declare variables n, key, i, and found = 0.

Ask the user to enter the number of elements n.

Declare an integer array of size n.

Ask the user to enter all array elements.

Ask the user to input the element (key) to search for.

Use a for loop from i = 0 to i < n:

If arr[i] == key:

Print the position (i + 1).

Set found = 1.

Break the loop.

After the loop, if found is still 0:

Print “Element not found.”

End the program.


**PROGRAM**  : 
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int n, key, i, found = 0;
printf("Enter number of elements: ");
scanf("%d", &n);
int arr[n];
printf("Enter elements: ");
for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
scanf("%d", &arr[i]);
printf("Enter element to search: ");
scanf("%d", &key);
for(i = 0; i < n; i++) {
if(arr[i] == key) {
printf("Element found at position %d\n", i + 1);
found = 1;
break;
}
}
if(!found)
printf("Element not found.\n");
return 0;
}

**SAMPLE OUTPUT** : 

Enter number of elements: 5

Enter elements: 10 25 30 45 50

Enter element to search: 30

Element found at position 3

**FINAL RESULT**

          The program successfully performs a linear search, checks whether the given element exists in the array, and displays the correct position if found.
